{"timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:58:52.028743+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "4d267184-ea94-4232-8e0f-40ecf4dbe287", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "answer": "Applicable controls for API security from the supplied set are the following (with brief explanation of how each applies):\n\n- [ia-9] Service Identification and Authentication \u2014 APIs and the services/apps that implement them must uniquely identify and authenticate before establishing communications. This addresses authenticating API clients, services, and backend components prior to API calls [ia-9].\n\n- [ia-13] Identity Providers and Authorization Servers \u2014 Use identity providers/authorization servers to manage identities, attributes, and access rights that support authentication and authorization decisions for API consumers (users, devices, NPEs) per organizational policy and mechanisms (e.g., OAuth/OIDC deployments) [ia-13].\n\n- [ia-5.2] Public Key-based Authentication \u2014 When APIs use public-key mechanisms (mutual TLS, client certificates), enforce protection of private keys, map authenticated identities to accounts, validate PKI certificate paths and statuses, and cache revocation data as needed for API authentication [ia-5.2].\n\n- [ac-20.1] Limits on Authorized Use \u2014 Permit external systems or third-party integrations to access organization APIs only after verifying that the external system implements required controls or after retaining approved connection/processing agreements, covering third\u2011party API consumers and federated integrations [ac-20.1].\n\n- [ac-17.4] Privileged Commands and Access \u2014 Restrict and authorize execution of privileged API operations or remote privileged access; require formats that provide assessable evidence and document rationale in the system security plan (applies to privileged API endpoints and admin interfaces) [ac-17.4].\n\n- [sa-4] Acquisition Process \u2014 Ensure API-related acquisitions (APIs, API gateways, cloud services) include security/privacy requirements, strength and assurance requirements, controls, documentation, responsibility allocation, and acceptance criteria in contracts [sa-4].\n\n- [sa-4.12] Data Ownership \u2014 In contracts for API-hosting or API-managed services, include data ownership and require removal/return of organizational data on contract termination, which applies to APIs that store/process organizational data with contractors [sa-4.12].\n\n- [sa-17] Developer Security and Privacy Architecture and Design \u2014 Require API developers to produce design/specifications and security architecture that align with enterprise architecture and clearly describe security functionality and control allocation across API components [sa-17].\n\n- [sa-15] Development Process, Standards, and Tools \u2014 Require API developers to follow a documented secure development process that explicitly addresses security/privacy requirements, specifies standards/tools/configurations, manages changes to those tools/processes, and periodically review them against organization-defined security/privacy requirements [sa-15].\n\n- [sa-9.3] Establish and Maintain Trust Relationship with Providers \u2014 For externally provided API services or platform providers (API gateways, cloud APIs), establish, document, and maintain trust relationships based on organization-defined security/privacy requirements and conditions [sa-9.3].\n\nIf you need, I can map these controls to specific API controls (authentication, authorization, transport protection, client credential management, onboarding/contract clauses, developer requirements) using only the controls above.", "latency_ms": 9662.9, "document_count": 10, "citations": ["ia-9", "ia-13", "ia-5.2", "ac-20.1", "ac-17.4", "sa-4", "sa-4.12", "sa-17", "sa-15", "sa-9.3"], "is_fallback": false}
