{"timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:58:57.408852+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "8ab54db6-d436-444c-813e-b6bf81e00c4f", "query": "What policies relate to logging and monitoring?", "answer": "The supplied controls that relate to logging and monitoring are:\n\n- [pe-6] Monitoring Physical Access \u2014 requires monitoring physical access, reviewing physical access logs at an organization-defined frequency and on specified events, and coordinating review results with incident response [pe-6].\n\n- [au-2] Event Logging \u2014 defines identification of loggable event types, coordination with other entities for selection criteria, specification of which event types are logged and when, rationale for adequacy of selected event types for after\u2011the\u2011fact investigations, and periodic review/update of logged event types [au-2].\n\n- [cm-11.3] Automated Enforcement and Monitoring \u2014 requires enforcing and monitoring compliance with software installation policies via organization-defined automated mechanisms (this is a form of monitoring of configuration/software state) [cm-11.3].\n\n- [ma-4] Nonlocal Maintenance \u2014 requires approving and monitoring nonlocal maintenance activities and maintaining records for those activities (recordkeeping and monitoring of remote maintenance sessions) [ma-4].\n\nNote: [ac-25] Reference Monitor is about enforcing access control policy via a tamperproof monitor; it is not itself a logging or monitoring control and does not mandate logging/monitoring activities, so it is not listed as a logging/monitoring policy here [ac-25].", "latency_ms": 5379.0, "document_count": 5, "citations": ["pe-6", "au-2", "cm-11.3", "ma-4", "ac-25"], "is_fallback": false}
